<paragraph blockId="16.[369,539,1267,1326]" box="[369,539,1267,1293]" pageId="16" pageNumber="697">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Scopoli" authorityYear="1777" box="[369,459,1267,1293]" class="Amphibia" isUncertain="true" kingdom="Animalia" order="Caudata" pageId="16" pageNumber="697" phylum="Chordata" rank="order">Caudata</taxonomicName>
? indet.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="697" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="16.[369,539,1267,1326]" box="[407,500,1299,1326]" pageId="16" pageNumber="697">
(
<figureCitation box="[416,491,1299,1326]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="17.[132,143,1986,2003]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,215,1904]" captionTargetId="figure-29@17.[609,1070,965,1341]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIG. 11. — Vertebra of Caudata indet. from Angeac-Charente: A-F, (ANG M-71) in anterior (A), posterior (B), left lateral (C), right lateral (D), dorsal (E) and ventral (F) views. Scale bar: 2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902057" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902057/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="697">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[130,776,1364,2028]" box="[132,277,1364,1390]" pageId="16" pageNumber="697">DESCRIPTION</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[130,776,1364,2028]" lastBlockId="16.[811,1457,885,1103]" pageId="16" pageNumber="697">
Among the microvertebrates from Angeac-Charente, a specimen could be referred to Caudata. Indeed, the vertebra ANG M-71 (
<figureCitation box="[211,286,1459,1485]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="17.[132,143,1986,2003]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,215,1904]" captionTargetId="figure-29@17.[609,1070,965,1341]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIG. 11. — Vertebra of Caudata indet. from Angeac-Charente: A-F, (ANG M-71) in anterior (A), posterior (B), left lateral (C), right lateral (D), dorsal (E) and ventral (F) views. Scale bar: 2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902057" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902057/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="697">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
) is anteroposteriorly elongated, with a broad, almost circular cotyle (
<figureCitation box="[376,471,1491,1517]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="17.[132,143,1986,2003]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,215,1904]" captionTargetId="figure-29@17.[609,1070,965,1341]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIG. 11. — Vertebra of Caudata indet. from Angeac-Charente: A-F, (ANG M-71) in anterior (A), posterior (B), left lateral (C), right lateral (D), dorsal (E) and ventral (F) views. Scale bar: 2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902057" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902057/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="697">Fig. 11A</figureCitation>
) and with well-defined pre– and postzygapophyses. The posterior part of the centrum is abraded, but the vertebra is clearly procoelous. Two small subcentral foramina are present on the ventral face (
<figureCitation box="[671,762,1586,1613]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="17.[132,143,1986,2003]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,215,1904]" captionTargetId="figure-29@17.[609,1070,965,1341]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIG. 11. — Vertebra of Caudata indet. from Angeac-Charente: A-F, (ANG M-71) in anterior (A), posterior (B), left lateral (C), right lateral (D), dorsal (E) and ventral (F) views. Scale bar: 2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902057" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902057/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="697">Fig. 11F</figureCitation>
). The general shape, presence of transverse processes extending posterolaterally, and broad vertebral cotyle are reminiscent of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Rage et al. 1993)" baseAuthorityName="Rage" baseAuthorityYear="1993" box="[132,423,1682,1709]" class="Mammalia" family="Brandoniidae" genus="Brandonia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="16" pageNumber="697" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="caudata">
Caudata (
<bibRefCitation author="RAGE J. - C. &amp; MARSHALL L. G. &amp; GAYET M." box="[238,412,1682,1709]" journalOrPublisher="Geobios" pageId="16" pageNumber="697" pagination="515 - 519" part="26" refId="ref47329" refString="RAGE J. - C., MARSHALL L. G. &amp; GAYET M. 1993. - Enigmatic Caudata (Amphibia) from the Upper Cretaceous of Gondwana. Geobios 26: 515 - 519. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / S 0016 - 6995 (06) 80234 - 2" title="Enigmatic Caudata (Amphibia) from the Upper Cretaceous of Gondwana" type="journal article" year="1993">
Rage 
<emphasis box="[298,350,1682,1708]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="697">et al.</emphasis>
1993
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[435,559,1682,1709]" class="Mammalia" family="Brandoniidae" genus="Brandonia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="16" pageNumber="697" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="caudata">In Caudata</taxonomicName>
, the trunk vertebrae are, however, commonly opisthocoelous or amphicoelous and the procoelous condition is rare (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Estes" box="[532,647,1746,1772]" firstAuthor="Estes" pageId="16" pageNumber="697" refId="ref39109" refString="ESTES R. 1981. - Gymnophiona, Caudata, in WELLNHOFER P. (ed.), Encyclopedia of Paleoherpetology. Part 2. Gustav Fischer, Stuttgart, 115 p." type="book" year="1981">Estes 1981</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="RAGE J. - C. &amp; MARSHALL L. G. &amp; GAYET M." journalOrPublisher="Geobios" pageId="16" pageNumber="697" pagination="515 - 519" part="26" refId="ref47329" refString="RAGE J. - C., MARSHALL L. G. &amp; GAYET M. 1993. - Enigmatic Caudata (Amphibia) from the Upper Cretaceous of Gondwana. Geobios 26: 515 - 519. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / S 0016 - 6995 (06) 80234 - 2" title="Enigmatic Caudata (Amphibia) from the Upper Cretaceous of Gondwana" type="journal article" year="1993">
Rage 
<emphasis box="[723,775,1746,1772]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="697">et al.</emphasis>
1993
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Alloul" box="[200,380,1778,1804]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Alloul" pageId="16" pageNumber="697" pagination="384 - 388" refId="ref35490" refString="ALLOUL T., RAGE J. - C., HAMDIDOUCHE R. &amp; JALIL N. - E. 2018. - First report on Cretaceous vertebrates from the Algerian Kem Kem Beds. A new procoelous salamander from the Cenomanian, with remarks on African Caudata. Cretaceous Research 84: 384 - 388. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. cretres. 2017.11.019" type="journal article" year="2018">
Alloul 
<emphasis box="[270,320,1778,1804]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="697">et al.</emphasis>
2018
</bibRefCitation>
for examples of procoelous caudates). On the contrary, the procoelous condition is common within 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Oppel, 1811 SCINCOMORPHA Camp" authorityYear="1923" box="[132,237,1842,1868]" class="Reptilia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="16" pageNumber="697" phylum="Chordata" rank="order">Squamata</taxonomicName>
, to which this vertebra could be alternatively referred. Moreover, anterior basapophyses, which are present in many caudate groups (
<bibRefCitation author="Estes" box="[302,415,1905,1932]" firstAuthor="Estes" pageId="16" pageNumber="697" refId="ref39109" refString="ESTES R. 1981. - Gymnophiona, Caudata, in WELLNHOFER P. (ed.), Encyclopedia of Paleoherpetology. Part 2. Gustav Fischer, Stuttgart, 115 p." type="book" year="1981">Estes 1981</bibRefCitation>
), are not discernable, and the presence or absence of a notochordal pit, which is usually observed on caudate vertebrae (
<bibRefCitation author="Alloul" box="[369,555,1969,1995]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Alloul" pageId="16" pageNumber="697" pagination="384 - 388" refId="ref35490" refString="ALLOUL T., RAGE J. - C., HAMDIDOUCHE R. &amp; JALIL N. - E. 2018. - First report on Cretaceous vertebrates from the Algerian Kem Kem Beds. A new procoelous salamander from the Cenomanian, with remarks on African Caudata. Cretaceous Research 84: 384 - 388. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. cretres. 2017.11.019" type="journal article" year="2018">
Alloul 
<emphasis box="[441,493,1969,1995]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="697">et al.</emphasis>
2018
</bibRefCitation>
), cannot be inferred because of the abraded condyle. However, the left transverse process (= rib-bearer), although broken, has an expanded head (
<figureCitation box="[821,976,917,943]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="17.[132,143,1986,2003]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,215,1904]" captionTargetId="figure-29@17.[609,1070,965,1341]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIG. 11. — Vertebra of Caudata indet. from Angeac-Charente: A-F, (ANG M-71) in anterior (A), posterior (B), left lateral (C), right lateral (D), dorsal (E) and ventral (F) views. Scale bar: 2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902057" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902057/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="697">Fig. 11C, E, F</figureCitation>
), indicating that it may be bilobed as in salamanders, and a ridge extending between the transverse process and the condyle seems to be present, as in 
<taxonomicName authority="(Alloul et al. 2018)" baseAuthorityName="Alloul" baseAuthorityYear="2018" class="Mammalia" family="Brandoniidae" genus="Brandonia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="16" pageNumber="697" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="caudata">
Caudata (
<bibRefCitation author="Alloul" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Alloul" pageId="16" pageNumber="697" pagination="384 - 388" refId="ref35490" refString="ALLOUL T., RAGE J. - C., HAMDIDOUCHE R. &amp; JALIL N. - E. 2018. - First report on Cretaceous vertebrates from the Algerian Kem Kem Beds. A new procoelous salamander from the Cenomanian, with remarks on African Caudata. Cretaceous Research 84: 384 - 388. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. cretres. 2017.11.019" type="journal article" year="2018">
Alloul 
<emphasis box="[1408,1456,980,1006]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="697">et al.</emphasis>
2018
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, but the preservation is too poor to reach a conclusion. Thus, this vertebra is tentively referred to Caudata?, although an assignment to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Oppel, 1811 SCINCOMORPHA Camp" authorityYear="1923" box="[997,1101,1076,1102]" class="Reptilia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="16" pageNumber="697" phylum="Chordata" rank="order">Squamata</taxonomicName>
cannot be excluded.
</paragraph>
